					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">You mean the program bank register?  I don't either, but I assumed it was because my programs are all small, so there's no point putting anything but data (and sometimes not even that) anywhere outside the first bank.  But I code without subroutines, for speed, and I think I prefer to generate multiple specialized routines rather than generalize a single routine at the expense of speed, so I fully expect to use more than one bank for code in the finished game (if it ever gets finished...).  The official GSU map seems to have 16 Mb of LoROM from $80-$BF and 32 Mb of HiROM from $C0-$FF, so I think that's probably a reasonable way to divide up code and bulk data...<br /><br />I <em>have</em> used the data bank register, most notably in that overlay renderer.  It took up a sizeable chunk of WRAM, and using 24-bit addressing for the whole thing was just not going to fly...</div>

